<dl id="un1014g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="un1" href="#un1014">UN1: </a>  <a href="../../FF/unbs/un1all.htm#un1014g"> (NLI.3) 14(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Day &amp; night of Brahma 8640 mill. years, manvantara, <small>Not cancelled</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="un1014g"><li>Ulysses </li><li><a href="../../ulex/c/lexc.htm#un1014g">2021</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/c/c86.htm#un1014g">2017</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/c/c86.htm#un1014g">1986 (3.143f)</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/c/l22c.htm#un1014g">1922</a> </li><li><ms href="#un1014g">MS V.A.3-6</ms> </li><li>JJA 12:244 </li><li><a name="c11d" href="../udra/u3da.htm#c11d">Usage</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/c/c11d.htm#un1014g">Draft: 3.1</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">In The Secret Doctrine, (i. 719), we are told that after <mark>a Day and Night of Brahm&#257;, a period of 8,640 million years</mark>, a new sun rises triumphantly over a new Manvan&#7789;ara; hence if we may assume that the suns of our sidereal system, have, on the average, the same length of time to go through their cyclic changes, and that each phase of the cycle is evenly distributed in time, then the whole of the 10,000 million suns of our system, will advance into manifestation, or recede into pralaya, once in 8,640 million years, or in other words we shall have one such manifestation, or one such pralaya, on the average, every year. <small> <a name="THsep1910" href="/udra/udex.htm#THsep1910"><cite title="source">The Theosophist</cite></a> (September 1910), G. E. Sutcliffe, &ldquo;SCIENTIFIC NOTES&rdquo; p. 1614</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c07262b" href="../../../F/FF/fnbs/c07all.htm#c07262b">VI.C.07:262(b)</a> </dd> </dd></dl>
